WEBVTT

00:05.964 --> 00:09.009
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:09.009 --> 00:12.012
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:12.012 --> 00:15.057
<i>[rock music]</i>

00:15.057 --> 00:16.016
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:16.016 --> 00:17.476
<i>‐ My name is Tom Garden.</i>

00:17.476 --> 00:19.269
I've made over 150 knives.

00:19.269 --> 00:23.232
<i>99.9% have been made</i>
<i>of recycled material:</i>

00:23.232 --> 00:25.526
<i>lawn mower blade,</i>
<i>wrench, tool.</i>

00:25.526 --> 00:30.072
I am full of piss and vinegar
to go out and start hammering.

00:30.072 --> 00:31.573
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:31.573 --> 00:32.908
<i>‐ My name's Jason Anderson.</i>

00:32.908 --> 00:34.576
What I love about
bladesmithing is,

00:34.576 --> 00:36.870
<i>the interaction between</i>
<i>the smith and the steel.</i>

00:36.870 --> 00:39.665
<i>It's revealing what's inside</i>
<i>the steel</i>

00:39.665 --> 00:41.416
<i>to work between the two of us.</i>

00:41.416 --> 00:44.253
I'm looking forward to any
challenge that's brought up.

00:44.253 --> 00:46.088
<i>‐ My name is Sam Farnworth.</i>

00:46.088 --> 00:48.215
I have never used
a power hammer before,

00:48.215 --> 00:50.425
<i>so I'm excited</i>
<i>to be using big blue,</i>

00:50.425 --> 00:54.221
<i>and my dream of using one</i>
<i>will be finally fulfilled.</i>

00:54.221 --> 00:56.390
<i>And if I win, then I will</i>
<i>get one for myself.</i>

00:56.390 --> 00:57.891
[laughs]

00:57.891 --> 00:58.934
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:58.934 --> 01:00.310
<i>‐ My name's Mark Campana,</i>

01:00.310 --> 01:01.603
and I'm from Bath, Ohio,

01:01.603 --> 01:04.064
where I'm a full‐time
personal trainer.

01:04.064 --> 01:06.900
<i>I wanna do "Forged in Fire"</i>
<i>because I feel like</i>

01:06.900 --> 01:09.069
a lot of us waste time.

01:09.069 --> 01:10.612
<i>Right now I have</i>
<i>the opportunity,</i>

01:10.612 --> 01:12.864
and I wanna challenge myself.

01:12.864 --> 01:15.033
<i>And I'm ready to win.</i>

01:15.033 --> 01:17.119
‐ Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:17.119 --> 01:19.121
You're here to engage
in three timed rounds

01:19.121 --> 01:20.831
of edged weapon‐making
competition

01:20.831 --> 01:23.625
like no other on this planet,

01:23.625 --> 01:25.627
all in front of a panel
of expert judges

01:25.627 --> 01:26.962
who will tell us which of you

01:26.962 --> 01:28.297
is our next
"Forged in Fire" champion

01:28.297 --> 01:30.632
leaving here with a check
for $10,000.

01:30.632 --> 01:32.342
Let's go ahead and meet
your judges now.

01:32.342 --> 01:35.637
Up first, ABS Mastersmith,
J. Neilson.

01:35.637 --> 01:38.140
Next, Historic Weapons
Re‐creation Specialist

01:38.140 --> 01:39.266
David Baker.

01:39.266 --> 01:41.268
And last,
Edged Weapons specialist

01:41.268 --> 01:43.186
Doug Marcaida.

01:43.186 --> 01:46.565
Bladesmiths, this year marks
the 50th anniversary

01:46.565 --> 01:48.150
of NASA's Apollo missions

01:48.150 --> 01:50.235
and Neil Armstrong's
first steps on the moon.

01:50.235 --> 01:53.238
So with that in mind in this
first round of competition,

01:53.238 --> 01:55.324
you'll be forging one of these.

01:55.324 --> 01:57.993
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

01:57.993 --> 01:59.494
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:59.494 --> 02:03.832
<i>That is a Case & Sons M‐1</i>
<i>Astronaut Knife.</i>

02:03.832 --> 02:06.710
‐ Jeez, oh flip.
What did I get into?

02:06.710 --> 02:09.212
<i>‐ The M‐1 survival knife</i>
<i>has accompanied</i>

02:09.212 --> 02:11.423
<i>NASA's Gemini and Apollo</i>
<i>astronauts</i>

02:11.423 --> 02:13.383
<i>into space since 1965</i>

02:13.383 --> 02:15.344
<i>and has made nine trips</i>
<i>to the moon.</i>

02:15.344 --> 02:17.512
<i>When other military knives</i>
<i>didn't meet</i>

02:17.512 --> 02:19.139
<i>NASA's specific criteria,</i>

02:19.139 --> 02:21.183
<i>they commissioned this knife</i>
<i>to be made</i>

02:21.183 --> 02:23.185
<i>to their exact specifications.</i>

02:23.185 --> 02:25.729
<i>Featuring a high carbon</i>
<i>stainless steel machete blade</i>

02:25.729 --> 02:27.356
<i>with saw teeth</i>
<i>and a lightweight</i>

02:27.356 --> 02:28.815
<i>synthetic handle,</i>

02:28.815 --> 02:30.525
<i>the knife was built</i>
<i>to be razor sharp,</i>

02:30.525 --> 02:32.486
<i>withstand harsh conditions,</i>

02:32.486 --> 02:35.614
<i>and most importantly,</i>
<i>survive impact.</i>

02:35.614 --> 02:39.159
Gentlemen, today you'll have
to recreate that blade

02:39.159 --> 02:41.286
within the following
parameters.

02:41.995 --> 02:43.538
<i>The length of this blade</i>
<i>must be</i>

02:43.538 --> 02:45.248
<i>between eight and ten inches</i>
<i>as measured</i>

02:45.248 --> 02:46.875
<i>from tip to plunge line.</i>

02:46.875 --> 02:48.377
<i>The overall length</i>
<i>of this weapon</i>

02:48.377 --> 02:50.754
<i>may not exceed 22 inches.</i>

02:50.754 --> 02:53.006
<i>It must be at least</i>
<i>two inches wide at the belly,</i>

02:53.006 --> 02:56.510
<i>have a full tang,</i>
<i>and you must add a saw back</i>

02:56.510 --> 02:58.053
<i>by the end of round two.</i>

02:58.053 --> 02:59.721
Now let's talk about
what you're making

02:59.721 --> 03:01.723
these blades out of.

03:01.723 --> 03:03.809
You'll have to harvest
the steel that you need

03:03.809 --> 03:06.603
from these 52100 ball bearings.

03:06.603 --> 03:08.730
You'll have three hours
in which to complete your work.

03:08.730 --> 03:10.232
At the end
of those three hours,

03:10.232 --> 03:11.942
after the judges have
inspected your work,

03:11.942 --> 03:13.944
one of you will have
to surrender your blade

03:13.944 --> 03:15.445
and leave The Forge.

03:15.445 --> 03:16.571
Now, in the second round

03:16.571 --> 03:18.198
after you've had an opportunity

03:18.198 --> 03:20.283
to add handles to this piece
of survival gear,

03:20.283 --> 03:21.743
you will enter our first‐ever

03:21.743 --> 03:24.955
triple strength and durability
test...

03:24.955 --> 03:27.207
consisting of an earth tilling
test,

03:27.207 --> 03:31.086
a sheet metal stab,
a bamboo chop.

03:31.086 --> 03:33.463
And if your blades survive
those strength tests,

03:33.463 --> 03:36.716
we'll test them for sharpness
in an apple slice.

03:36.716 --> 03:39.094
Gentlemen, we've provided you
with the sample.

03:39.094 --> 03:40.470
We've provided you
with blueprints.

03:40.470 --> 03:41.930
Do your best work.

03:41.930 --> 03:46.017
This round starts
in three, two, one...launch.

03:46.017 --> 03:47.686
<i>[rock music]</i>

03:47.686 --> 03:51.273
‐ Oh, off to space.
[laughs]

03:51.273 --> 03:52.649
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:52.649 --> 03:55.235
‐ All right, so each one
of our smiths has to make

03:55.235 --> 03:58.905
an exact copy
of our M‐1 Astronaut's Knife

03:58.905 --> 04:02.784
out of those 52100 blobs
of steel.

04:02.784 --> 04:05.954
Harvesting the steel isn't
the biggest challenge here,

04:05.954 --> 04:07.497
is it?

04:07.497 --> 04:09.958
‐ No, you just gotta decide
what you wanna use.

04:09.958 --> 04:12.002
You could get a blade
close to that

04:12.002 --> 04:13.920
with the smaller ball bearing,

04:13.920 --> 04:15.422
but I'd go with the two‐inch

04:15.422 --> 04:16.923
just to have a little
sacrificial material.

04:16.923 --> 04:18.175
‐ Okay.

04:18.175 --> 04:19.259
‐ And I'm worried,
'cause it looks like

04:19.259 --> 04:20.802
Sam here might be going

04:20.802 --> 04:22.971
for the largest ball bearing
the way he's grinding.

04:22.971 --> 04:26.892
‐ The options for forging
my balls...

04:26.892 --> 04:29.269
[chuckling]

04:29.269 --> 04:30.228
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:30.228 --> 04:31.354
[clears throat]

04:31.354 --> 04:32.939
Moving on.

04:32.939 --> 04:35.150
<i>The option I am going</i>
<i>with is to forge the blade</i>

04:35.150 --> 04:39.362
<i>out of that one massive</i>
<i>three‐inch ball bearing.</i>

04:39.362 --> 04:41.615
‐ Sam just put in
about that much steel.

04:41.615 --> 04:45.786
How long is gonna take to heat
that steel up to the core?

04:45.786 --> 04:47.579
‐ About 15 minutes or so.

04:47.579 --> 04:49.998
‐ This is a good time
to make a strategy.

04:49.998 --> 04:52.125
‐ Well, you can see Sam‐‐
he's got his blueprint out,

04:52.125 --> 04:53.835
he's got his ruler out.

04:53.835 --> 04:55.337
Way to go.

04:55.337 --> 04:57.047
<i>‐ I feel like I'm off</i>
<i>to a great start.</i>

04:57.047 --> 04:58.298
Things are going great.

04:58.298 --> 04:59.466
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:59.466 --> 05:01.176
‐ I competed on
"Knife or Death."

05:01.176 --> 05:03.428
<i>I liked the fact</i>
<i>that I could make my blade</i>

05:03.428 --> 05:04.888
<i>ahead of time</i>
<i>for "Knife or Death"</i>

05:04.888 --> 05:06.556
<i>and bring it in</i>
<i>and destroy stuff,</i>

05:06.556 --> 05:07.808
<i>instead of being given</i>

05:07.808 --> 05:09.601
<i>a bunch of balls</i>
<i>welded together.</i>

05:09.601 --> 05:12.521
I realize that somebody made,
like, some kind of a weird,

05:12.521 --> 05:15.565
horrible puzzle out of the way
they welded this crap together,

05:15.565 --> 05:17.734
and I'm actually getting
pretty annoyed.

05:17.734 --> 05:20.570
<i>It's taking way too long</i>
<i>to get the ball</i>

05:20.570 --> 05:22.906
that I want out of this mess.

05:22.906 --> 05:24.407
<i>Well, I chose the large ball,</i>

05:24.407 --> 05:26.159
because I wanted to have
enough material.

05:26.159 --> 05:28.453
‐ The largest one,
you could probably make

05:28.453 --> 05:29.496
five of these blades.

05:29.496 --> 05:31.373
‐ Yep.

05:31.373 --> 05:34.668
‐ Whoever put these
balls together is evil.

05:34.668 --> 05:36.127
Jeez, oh flip!

05:36.127 --> 05:37.963
[saw buzzes]

05:37.963 --> 05:39.589
This sucks!

05:39.589 --> 05:41.883
This should not be this hard.

05:41.883 --> 05:44.052
<i>This is not the start</i>
<i>I wanted.</i>

05:44.052 --> 05:47.931
<i>I'm trying to get this done,</i>
<i>and I'm just fighting with it.</i>

05:47.931 --> 05:52.310
I need to calm down, rethink,
and do it one step at a time.

05:52.310 --> 05:54.521
[saw buzzes]

05:54.521 --> 05:56.147
I wanted the biggest ball.

05:56.147 --> 05:58.275
<i>That way I have material</i>
<i>to work with,</i>

05:58.275 --> 06:00.402
<i>and I could shorten it</i>
<i>as needed.</i>

06:00.402 --> 06:01.820
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:01.820 --> 06:03.572
<i>[upbeat rock music]</i>

06:03.572 --> 06:05.949
<i>‐ The three‐inch ball bearing</i>
<i>is really speaking to me</i>

06:05.949 --> 06:07.492
<i>as the piece I need to use.</i>

06:07.492 --> 06:09.077
I'm gonna get more
than enough steel out of it

06:09.077 --> 06:10.745
to make my billet.

06:10.745 --> 06:12.914
<i>My first thought is,</i>
<i>"I can cut through this thing</i>

06:12.914 --> 06:14.541
<i>pretty quick."</i>

06:14.541 --> 06:16.668
I was incorrect.

06:16.668 --> 06:18.962
I'm getting killed here.

06:18.962 --> 06:20.714
<i>There's multiple welds</i>
<i>per ball,</i>

06:20.714 --> 06:23.216
and the welds are
in odd places,

06:23.216 --> 06:26.553
<i>so it's almost impossible</i>
<i>to hit 'em with the sawblade.</i>

06:26.553 --> 06:28.138
‐ All right,
I love me a chop saw,

06:28.138 --> 06:30.432
but I think the angle grinders
were a better bet.

06:30.432 --> 06:32.601
And I think Jason's figuring
that out now.

06:32.601 --> 06:33.518
‐ [bleep]

06:33.518 --> 06:34.811
I'm looking at the time.

06:34.811 --> 06:36.855
I'm looking at this
massive steel

06:36.855 --> 06:38.481
<i>that I still have to try</i>
<i>to get apart.</i>

06:38.481 --> 06:40.775
<i>It's starting to worry me.</i>

06:40.775 --> 06:42.110
<i>[bleep]</i>
<i>Finally.</i>

06:42.110 --> 06:43.904
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:43.904 --> 06:48.366
‐ How did Sam get in The Forge
so much more quickly

06:48.366 --> 06:50.327
than everybody else?

06:50.327 --> 06:53.038
‐ Young, he's got more energy.

06:53.038 --> 06:54.998
<i>[exciting music]</i>

06:54.998 --> 06:57.292
<i>‐ My steel's finally come up</i>
<i>to temperature.</i>

06:57.292 --> 06:58.585
As I'm drawing it out,

06:58.585 --> 07:00.045
I'm flipping it
every which way,

07:00.045 --> 07:03.006
so I can ultimately end up
with a rectangle.

07:03.006 --> 07:04.549
‐ We've got some steel
on the move,

07:04.549 --> 07:07.260
some ball bearings that are
no longer ball bearings.

07:07.260 --> 07:09.471
‐ I started by squaring it off
in the press,

07:09.471 --> 07:11.306
'cause that's
a little more controlled.

07:11.306 --> 07:13.892
<i>And now I'm just kind of</i>
<i>drawing out the bar</i>

07:13.892 --> 07:15.018
<i>and keeping it the width</i>
<i>I want</i>

07:15.018 --> 07:16.478
<i>and then thinning it down.</i>

07:16.478 --> 07:18.480
‐ There's a lot of times
we get blades

07:18.480 --> 07:19.814
that are too thick,

07:19.814 --> 07:21.983
and we've got
a specifically thin knife

07:21.983 --> 07:25.945
for multiuse,
including chopping and prying.

07:25.945 --> 07:28.657
<i>‐ Using big blue is basically</i>
<i>a dream come true.</i>

07:28.657 --> 07:30.367
It's just probably
one of the most satisfying

07:30.367 --> 07:33.411
things in the world.

07:33.411 --> 07:35.830
<i>‐ My steel is</i>
<i>finally hot enough.</i>

07:35.830 --> 07:38.124
<i>I can take it to the press.</i>

07:38.124 --> 07:39.584
<i>It moved</i>
<i>a hell of a lot easier</i>

07:39.584 --> 07:41.544
than I thought it was going to.

07:41.544 --> 07:43.630
‐ Scared the heck out of me
by taking a ball bearing

07:43.630 --> 07:46.466
and just wrenching down on it
with the press

07:46.466 --> 07:49.636
to almost a burger patty
in one heat.

07:49.636 --> 07:52.305
That worries me that he might
have put some stress fractures

07:52.305 --> 07:53.431
in his blade.

07:53.431 --> 07:55.016
<i>‐ The next few steps are just</i>

07:55.016 --> 07:56.726
<i>going back and forth</i>
<i>between The Forge</i>

07:56.726 --> 07:58.603
<i>and the power hammer</i>
<i>and maybe occasionally</i>

07:58.603 --> 08:00.021
<i>using the press.</i>

08:00.021 --> 08:03.024
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

08:03.024 --> 08:04.526
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:04.526 --> 08:06.945
‐ Bladesmiths!
One hour has elapsed.

08:06.945 --> 08:10.031
You have two hours remaining
to finish your blades!

08:10.031 --> 08:11.533
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:11.533 --> 08:13.910
‐ Jason was actually
our last one in The Forge,

08:13.910 --> 08:16.496
but he seems to be
moving along nicely now.

08:16.496 --> 08:17.997
<i>‐ One of the best things</i>

08:17.997 --> 08:19.374
<i>about a large mass of steel</i>
<i>like this</i>

08:19.374 --> 08:21.292
is the heat retention is there.

08:21.292 --> 08:24.838
I'm happy because I get to work
this steel in the press

08:24.838 --> 08:26.047
<i>for two to three minutes,</i>

08:26.047 --> 08:27.924
<i>where if it was a flat billet,</i>

08:27.924 --> 08:30.593
I might have 30 seconds
before the heat is gone.

08:30.593 --> 08:33.179
<i>The only major concern I got</i>
<i>at the moment is just</i>

08:33.179 --> 08:37.350
getting the point done
and not overheating my steel.

08:38.518 --> 08:40.687
‐ Big swings from Mark
over there.

08:40.687 --> 08:42.147
‐ That steel's so thin,

08:42.147 --> 08:43.565
you don't need to be hitting it
that hard.

08:43.565 --> 08:44.983
I mean, I'd be tapping
that steel.

08:44.983 --> 08:46.776
‐ He's down to
a quarter‐inch thick,

08:46.776 --> 08:48.528
so drawing that blade out
is gonna be

08:48.528 --> 08:49.738
really tough for him to do.

08:49.738 --> 08:51.281
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:51.281 --> 08:53.908
‐ At this point
my biggest concern is,

08:53.908 --> 08:55.785
<i>the replica is really thin.</i>

08:55.785 --> 08:58.079
<i>So I'm really trying to get it</i>
<i>as close to</i>

08:58.079 --> 09:00.874
the finished thickness now.

09:00.874 --> 09:04.627
‐ Really, these guys should be
aiming for thin,

09:04.627 --> 09:07.881
lightweight,
but very, very strong blades

09:07.881 --> 09:11.176
because weight was
such a huge consideration

09:11.176 --> 09:15.180
for any NASA mission
and still is to this day.

09:15.180 --> 09:17.557
Bladesmiths!
90 minutes has elapsed.

09:17.557 --> 09:19.267
That is half the time
in this round!

09:19.267 --> 09:20.477
[machinery buzzing]

09:20.477 --> 09:22.103
‐ Tom's got a frickin' sword.

09:22.103 --> 09:24.064
‐ I'm drawing out my billet.

09:24.064 --> 09:27.734
It's growing longer and longer
and longer.

09:27.734 --> 09:31.613
‐ Tom's steel is looking
wicked long and hot and unruly.

09:31.613 --> 09:35.909
‐ I am having a heck of a time
to get this billet straight.

09:38.536 --> 09:41.581
<i>My billet is way longer</i>
<i>than it needs to be.</i>

09:41.581 --> 09:45.502
I just need to cut it down
to a more workable size.

09:45.502 --> 09:47.462
<i>[rock music]</i>

09:47.462 --> 09:49.923
‐ If he cuts it down,
he can manage it easier.

09:49.923 --> 09:51.049
‐ Exactly.

09:51.049 --> 09:53.718
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:53.718 --> 09:55.428
‐ There we go.
‐ There ya go.

09:55.428 --> 09:56.888
<i>[exciting rock music]</i>

09:56.888 --> 09:58.890
‐ Bladesmiths!
Two hours has elapsed.

09:58.890 --> 10:01.893
You have one hour remaining
to finish your work.

10:01.893 --> 10:04.562
<i>‐ I feel like my blade is</i>
<i>in a really good spot</i>

10:04.562 --> 10:05.772
for profile grinding.

10:05.772 --> 10:08.191
I forged it fairly close
to general form,

10:08.191 --> 10:10.276
<i>and now it's ready</i>
<i>to just refine that.</i>

10:10.276 --> 10:12.487
‐ It's nice to see that Sam has
that blueprint

10:12.487 --> 10:15.198
literally at his feet.
‐ Oh, yeah.

10:15.198 --> 10:16.783
<i>‐ I grind a little bit</i>

10:16.783 --> 10:18.409
<i>and then check</i>
<i>with the blueprint,</i>

10:18.409 --> 10:19.911
<i>because it's critical</i>
<i>to get it</i>

10:19.911 --> 10:21.746
as close to the blueprint
as possible.

10:21.746 --> 10:24.749
<i>‐ The great thing about</i>
<i>this particular blade is that</i>

10:24.749 --> 10:26.042
it's multifunctional.

10:26.042 --> 10:28.294
<i>It is a survival knife</i>

10:28.294 --> 10:30.463
that was packed
into the survival kits

10:30.463 --> 10:32.257
of every Apollo capsule.

10:32.257 --> 10:33.591
If they were thrown off course

10:33.591 --> 10:35.552
into a contingency
landing site,

10:35.552 --> 10:38.596
those small machetes were
the survival tool

10:38.596 --> 10:40.807
that the astronauts would have
had to rely on

10:40.807 --> 10:42.433
if they made landfall.

10:42.433 --> 10:43.476
‐ Yeah.

